Solid priorities for fragile states
LONDON/MONROVIA/KIGALI – No country has been spared the repercussions of the COVID-19.
However, the most "fragile" states in the world face a particularly complex set of issues.
In fact, before the pandemic began, Yemen, Sudan, Haiti, Sierra Leone, Myanmar, Afghanistan, Venezuela, and other countries were already grappling with poverty, conflicts, corruption, and a deficient public administration.
Today, these elements leave these countries ill-equipped to manage the COVID-19 crisis.
Each country needs precisely what fragile states lack in order to navigate the pandemic: an effective state apparatus capable of developing and implementing an action plan, an efficient police force to enforce rules, social programs providing funds and supplies, and healthcare services to treat infected individuals.
The lack of state resources is immediately apparent in the field of public health.
While Europe has 4,000 intensive care beds per million inhabitants, several African regions have only five per million inhabitants.
Mali possesses only three ventilators for the entire country.
An effective response also requires confidence in the State's intervention.
However, in addition to its lack of resources, the public administration of most fragile states does not enjoy much popular support.
In countries emerging from a conflict or suffering from endemic corruption, many people will hesitate to support the government even if it proves capable of governing.
A strong private sector is also an essential component of effective and solid states.
Citizens should be able to work to support their families, and the state should be able to collect tax revenues to assist those who cannot.
However, in fragile states, the formal economy is not sufficiently present to meet these needs.
Earlier in the crisis, there was hope that some fragile states could avoid the worst health consequences of COVID-19 due to their youthful demographic weight and geographical remoteness.
However, as co-presidents of the new Council on State Fragility, we must acknowledge that this was not the case.
In recent weeks, Sudan, South Sudan, Somalia, and Yemen have all experienced infection and mortality rates rivaling those of developed countries hit hardest by the coronavirus.
Worse still, the economic consequences of the pandemic will certainly be more severe for fragile states. They will not be solely the result of national lockdowns, but also of what is happening abroad.
Trade with countries like China has declined, remittances from abroad have fallen, basic commodity prices and oil revenues have collapsed, and deficits are accumulating.
Since fragile states rely on imports for the majority of their food, talk of "hunger" and even "famine" is becoming increasingly common.
We should now understand that the problems of less affluent countries become most often global problems whether in the form of massive migrations, criminal or terrorist organizations, or economic repercussions.
Given that half of the impoverished population will live in fragile states by 2030, these problems will continue to worsen.
This is why the Council on State Fragility has made it its absolute priority to draw attention to the specific challenges these countries must overcome.
The council, composed of former world leaders, ministers, diplomats, business personalities, academics, and development organization presidents, will combine cutting-edge research with meticulous political knowledge. Its goal is to guide national and international policymakers who will determine how fragile states navigate this crisis and address their broader and deeper challenges.
Decentralization, adaptability, and wise use of data will be essentials.
For example, it is widely proven that "targeted lockdowns" of local outbreaks are often more appropriate than national lockdowns.
Such knowledge could prove crucial for fragile states.
However, we must act quickly before the critical phase of the pandemic in the West comes to an end and the sense of urgency fades.
We propose five recommendations.
First, access to social protection must be simpler and faster.
Sometimes, this will be synonymous with universal eligibility rather than precise targeting.
Mobile telecommunications networks should be leveraged to collect information on immediate needs and to disburse small regular payments (although of limited duration).
Second, national food production should be encouraged.
For example, Sierra Leone, which cultivated rice, has become increasingly dependent in recent decades.
In general, Africa accounts for 60% of unused arable land in the world.
Local food crop production initiatives must be rapidly scaled up significantly.
Thirdly, as soon as vaccine production begins, the international community must ensure that fragile states are not excluded from the market by wealthier countries.
When the threat is a contagious pathogen, no country is safe unless all are safe.
We must advocate and accelerate the production of multiple vaccines to ensure rapid and widespread distribution.
Fourthly, fragile states' businesses need immediate assistance.
As noted by the financial institutions most involved in international development; small enterprises in less affluent countries are often neglected and bear the adverse consequences of broader goals and rules (since it is easier to achieve a goal by investing in larger projects in bigger economies).
However, it is precisely these small enterprises that require larger investments.
Finally, the G20 should do more to support heavily indebted fragile states that are forced to choose between paying their foreign creditors or saving their populations.
It is expected that countries receiving bilateral development aid will have to repay approximately 40 billion dollars to private and public creditors this year alone.
To prevent this financial shock, we urge all G20 members to suspend accumulated debts not only until next year, but also until the end of the crisis.
Moreover, it is essential that all fragile states obtain emergency financing to support their efforts to contain COVID-19 and mitigate its economic repercussions—particularly those countries that do not typically have access to funding from the World Bank or the International Monetary Fund.
The COVID-19 pandemic will exacerbate existing problems in all fragile states around the world.
However, if the international community reacts promptly, we can mitigate the worst consequences of the pandemic.
If there is one lesson to be learned from this crisis, it is that livelihoods and lives will be saved if we move faster than the virus.
